ownedComment.body: See https://github.com/ISO-TC204/iso14812 for the Conceptual Data Model

Each specialization of a SensedValue should define a "value" attribute with the preferred units for the reading. In most cases, the preferred units should be based on SI-units with a decimal offset to allow an integer representation. For example, units might be metres, kilometres, centimetres, etc. and the preferred value would always be an integer. When converting values from an implementation using a physical data model that is based on different units, the value will need to be converted by a formula and the loss of accuracy will need to be reflected in the accuracy (e.g., if the PDM reports a value in meters (e.g., 5m) with an accuracy of +/- 1 meter, and the LDM prefers centimetres, the reported value would be multiplied by 100 (e.g., 500 cm) and the new accuracy would be adjusted to +/- 100 centimetres.
The SensedValue is a composite of all source data from sensors. Each sensor may have its own reading, but the physical object fuses all relevant data together to report a single SensedValue

Phenomena should be stereotyped as <<phenomenon>> and should always represent elemental concepts. A data model class reports on a phenomenon should have a <<measures>> association with the <<phenomenon>> class so that the model records the association and we capture all ways that phenomena are measured.

General structure for reporting observed data.
Any PhysicalObject, as defined by the architecture, can report on a number of SensedValues. Each SensedValue is associated with a type (e.g., in this case ambientAirPressure) and a location (e.g., allows reporting of values at different locations when needed; in this example, "ambient" would always have location 0). The type of SensedValue dictates which specialization is used. In the case of ambientAirPressure, the specialized type of SensedValue used would be the SensedAmbientAirPressure. Based on the rules of specialization, this class automatically contains all of the attributes defined within its parents (e.g., value from SensedPressure and accuracy among others from SensedValue). The SensedValue is determined from 1 or more Sensors (which have various attributes not shown here).
While this example focuses on the SensedAmbientAirPressure, it should be able to serve as a general template for most readings of sensed phenomena. I've even included vehicleHeading and vehicleSpeed - but I think Position needs to be handled separately due to differences in confidence and accuracy meta-data.
